{{nihongo|'''''Akira'''''|アキラ}} is a 1988 [[Adventure game|adventure]] video game by [[TOSE]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Family Computer]] console exclusively in Japan.<ref name="famitsu.com">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=19713|script-title=ja:アキラ [ファミコン]|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|publisher=[[Enterbrain Inc.]]|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801064207/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=19713|archive-date=2018-08-01|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> It is based on ''[[Akira (1988 film)|Akira]]'', the 1988 animated film version of [[Katsuhiro Otomo]]'s [[Akira (manga)|manga of the same name]].

== Plot ==
The player takes the role of Kaneda, who begins the game when his motorcycle gang is taken into police custody after the abduction of their friend Tetsuo by the military.

==Gameplay==
Progress in the game is made by selecting actions from a list. The current location is depicted in a static image, often redrawn from the film. Progress can be recorded with the help of [[password (video games)|passwords]].

== Development ==
The game was developed by TOSE and published by Taito.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/nes/577202-akira/data|title=Akira Release Information for NES|website=GameFAQs|access-date=2020-11-07}}</ref>

== Release ==
The game was released in Japan on December 24, 1988.<ref name="famitsu.com" /> It was released only 5 months after the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.retrogamer.net/retro_games80/akira-famicom/|title=Akira |website=Retro Gamer|date=December 19, 2011|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> The release coincided with the height of the popularity of the ''Akira'' series.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Hilliard|first=Kyle |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/12/18/i-want-an-akira-video-game.aspx|title=I Want An Akira Video Game|magazine=Game Informer|date=July 16, 2018 |access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref>

==Reception==
''Akira'' was given a poor total score of 17 out of 40 from the panel of four reviewers of ''[[Famitsu|Famicom Tsūshin]]'' magazine.<ref name="famitsu.com" /><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=[[Famitsu|Famicom Tsūshin]] |publisher=[[Enterbrain]], [[Tokuma]] |date=6 January 1989 |title=Cross Review |issue=65 |page=19 |language=ja}}</ref>

